              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> Like its Hebrew, Aramaic, Syriac, and Nabatean cognates from the root<em> Sh-L-M</em>—the Arabic <em>Muslim</em> comes from the etymologically identical root <em>S-L-M</em>—to be a <em>Muslim</em> means to be “at Peace with God” because of one’s “surrender” and “submission” to Him, making that person, in Biblical terms, one of “God’s true Friends.” In this sense, the closely related Hebrew, <em>Meshullām</em>, which is directly related in the Bible to “Servant of the Lord” (<em>‘Ebhedh-YHWH</em>; Arabic: <em>‘Abd-al-Rabb</em>) means “Friend of God by virtue of being at Peace with Him through submission” (see: Isaiah, 42:19; Ezra, 8:16; 10:15, 29; Nehemiah, 3:4; 6:18). Likewise, the Biblical <em>Meshullēmeth</em> for “Friend of God” (2 Kings, 21:19) and<strong> </strong><em>Meshelemiyāh </em>and<em> Meshelemiyāhû</em> stand for the one “whom the Lord repays” or the one “whom the Lord treats like a friend [because of his submission to God]” (1 Chronicles, 9:21; 26:1, 29), and this relationship of Divine Friendship through Peace and submission is also expressed in the Herbrew personal names <em>Shelumîēl</em> (Numbers, 1:6; 2:12) <em>Shelemiyāh </em>and <em>Shelemiyāhû</em> (1 Chronicles, 26:14). Syriac uses the verb <em>shelem</em>, <em>neshlam</em> for “following a doctrine, confession, or Divine Book.” It also means “to submit” or “surrender” to the Lord in the sense of giving oneself up to God as in the expression: “<em>Shelem napheshu la-Alāhā</em>” (He turned himself over to God). Syriac—like Arabic—has the fourth form<em> ashlem</em>, which means to “make Peace through surrender as in: “<em>Ashlem napheshhu</em>, meainging “he devoted himself or gave himself up to something, which—as in Arabic—is also used for “becoming a Muslim,” while “<em>Mashlemān</em>”<em> </em>and “<em>Mashlemānā</em>” are used for a person or thing that has been  made whole, completed, and filled” as well as to be a Muslim.  </p>",
