              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> <strong><em>A Syntopicon: An Index to The Great Ideas</em></strong> is a two-volume index first published by Mortimer Adler in 1371/1952 as part of the collection <em>Great Books of the Western World.</em> The terms “<em>syntopicon</em>” and “Great Ideas” were both coined for this undertaking. Adler’s <em>Syntopicon</em> was intended to galvanize the Great Books series, while also making it more marketable. Adler rightly believed that the <em>Syntopicon </em>would be “revolutionary,” and the labors expended on the work consumed several years of his life and those of his team of more than one hundred researchers. The book’s release, Adler surmised, would be comparable to the publication of the first dictionaries and encyclopedias in the Western world. He hoped that <em>The Syntopicon</em> would do for “ideas” what previous reference works had done for words and facts. Indeed, Adler’s colleague and co-worker Robert Maynard Hutchins (d. 1397/1977), president of the University of Chicago, believed that the effect of the <em>Syntopicon</em> would be so great that it would be “powerful enough to save the world from self-destruction.” </p>",
